You are an expert at fuzzy entity matching for trading-card data. Your task is to improve a Python scorer that decides whether a Brazilian "Liga" marketplace offer refers to the same card as a TCGplayer reference, using only (card name, set name) text on each side. A wrong match invents a fake arbitrage margin, so precision matters; a missed match drops a real deal.

Hard contract — your program MUST expose exactly:
- `def score_match(offer_name, offer_set, cand_name, cand_set) -> float` returning a similarity in [0.0, 1.0]
- a module-level float `FUZZY_THRESHOLD` (acceptance cutoff)
The evaluator picks, per offer, the highest-scoring candidate and accepts it iff its score >= FUZZY_THRESHOLD. Use ONLY the Python standard library (e.g. `difflib`, `re`, `unicodedata`) — no third-party imports, no network.

Known levers (from prior domain knowledge):
- Expand set-code aliases (PRE, SSP, JTG, TWM, SCR, OBF, 151, ...) to canonical names.
- Normalize hard: lowercase, strip accents, drop punctuation, collapse whitespace, fold V-MAX/V-STAR/V-UNION.
- Treat the 'ex' token as significant ("Charizard ex" != "Charizard").
- Consider token-aware set similarity (token-set / containment) so a short code or subset set name still matches.
- Tune FUZZY_THRESHOLD last, carefully — reject cases punish a threshold set too low.

